ssimilate into American political life. Jones-Correa reexamines assumptions about Latino politics and the diversity of Latino populations in the United States, about the role of informal politics in immigrant communities, and about gender differences in approaches to political activity.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mrz 2024) 0aCitizenshipzNew York (State)zNew York. 0aHispanic AmericanszNew York (State)zNew YorkxPolitics and government. 0aImmigrantsxPolitical activityzNew York (State)zNew York. 4aLatin American & Caribbean Studies. 4aPolitical Science & Political History. 4aU.S. History.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Archive Pre-2000z978311053617140uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/978150173134140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501731341423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781501731341/original  a978-3-11-053617-1  Cornell University Press Archive Pre-2000b2000  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_PPALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles